article.headline: Defending champs lose third straight
article.linkText: Miller time: 3-pointer wins it for Fever on the road
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Kelly Miller regained her shooting
touch quickly.

A game after struggling mightily against Charlotte, Miller made
all of her 3-point attempts, including one with 0.6 seconds left
gave the Indiana Fever a 69-68 victory over the Detroit Shock on
Tuesday night.

"It felt really good," said Miller, who was 2-of-11 against
the Sting. "It's exciting to hit a shot like that to beat a team
like Detroit."

Miller inbounded the ball to Tamika Catchings, who drove to the
basket before flipping the ball back to Miller on the left baseline
for the game-winning jumper.

"I told Tamika to get the ball and go to the basket," Indiana
coach Brian Winters said. "Kelly slid down the sideline, so Tamika
could either get her own shot or dish to Kelly. She made the right
decision."

Deanna Nolan's long triple at the buzzer bounced off the rim.
The defending WNBA champions have lost three straight and are 1-5
at home.

Catchings led the Fever with 19 points and Miller added 17.
Natalie Williams scored 11, but did not have a point after
halftime.

Swin Cash had 17 for Detroit, which lost starting point guard
Elaine Powell in the first half to a right foot injury. She is
day-to-day.

"I think a lot of things are going on right now that are
unexplainable," said Shock captain Swin Cash. "We just have to
refocus and keep going."

The Fever missed 10 straight shots early in the second half, and
Detroit took advantage, going on a 10-0 run that included two
baskets from Cash and went ahead 52-44.

Indiana got as close as two, but Catchings and Kristen Rasmussen
both missed tying jumpers before Cash's lay-in made it 68-64 with
1:19 left.

Catchings made it a two-point game again with 42 seconds to go,
and Kelly Schumacher blocked Nolan's shot at the other end.

Indiana called timeout with 7.3 seconds to play, setting up
Miller's shot.

"I'm really happy for Kelly," Winters said. "She's been
struggling with her shooting lately, so that was a great shot for
her."
